{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"On the 30th of May, 1832,"},{"time":4000,"text":"a gunshot was heard"},{"time":6000,"text":"ringing out across the 13th arrondissement in Paris."},{"time":9000,"text":"(Gunshot)"},{"time":10000,"text":"A peasant, who was walking to market that morning,"},{"time":13000,"text":"ran towards where the gunshot had come from,"},{"time":15000,"text":"and found a young man writhing in agony on the floor,"},{"time":19000,"text":"clearly shot by a dueling wound."},{"time":22000,"text":"The young man's name was Evariste Galois."},{"time":25000,"text":"He was a well-known revolutionary in Paris at the time."},{"time":29000,"text":"Galois was taken to the local hospital"},{"time":32000,"text":"where he died the next day in the arms of his brother."},{"time":35000,"text":"And the last words he said to his brother were,"},{"time":37000,"text":"\"Don't cry for me, Alfred."},{"time":39000,"text":"I need all the courage I can muster"},{"time":41000,"text":"to die at the age of 20.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":45000,"text":"It wasn't, in fact, revolutionary politics"},{"time":47000,"text":"for which Galois was famous."},{"time":49000,"text":"But a few years earlier, while still at school,"},{"time":52000,"text":"he'd actually cracked one of the big mathematical"},{"time":54000,"text":"problems at the time."},{"time":56000,"text":"And he wrote to the academicians in Paris,"},{"time":58000,"text":"trying to explain his theory."},{"time":60000,"text":"But the academicians couldn't understand anything that he wrote."},{"time":63000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":64000,"text":"This is how he wrote most of his mathematics."}]},{"cues":[{"time":67000,"text":"So, the night before that duel, he realized"},{"time":69000,"text":"this possibly is his last chance"},{"time":72000,"text":"to try and explain his great breakthrough."},{"time":74000,"text":"So he stayed up the whole night, writing away,"},{"time":77000,"text":"trying to explain his ideas."},{"time":79000,"text":"And as the dawn came up and he went to meet his destiny,"},{"time":82000,"text":"he left this pile of papers on the table for the next generation."},{"time":86000,"text":"Maybe the fact that he stayed up all night doing mathematics"},{"time":89000,"text":"was the fact that he was such a bad shot that morning and got killed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":92000,"text":"But contained inside those documents"},{"time":94000,"text":"was a new language, a language to understand"},{"time":97000,"text":"one of the most fundamental concepts"},{"time":99000,"text":"of science -- namely symmetry."},{"time":102000,"text":"Now, symmetry is almost nature's language."},{"time":104000,"text":"It helps us to understand so many"},{"time":106000,"text":"different bits of the scientific world."},{"time":108000,"text":"For example, molecular structure."},{"time":110000,"text":"What crystals are possible,"},{"time":112000,"text":"we can understand through the mathematics of symmetry."}]},{"cues":[{"time":116000,"text":"In microbiology you really don't want to get a symmetrical object,"},{"time":118000,"text":"because they are generally rather nasty."},{"time":120000,"text":"The swine flu virus, at the moment, is a symmetrical object."},{"time":123000,"text":"And it uses the efficiency of symmetry"},{"time":125000,"text":"to be able to propagate itself so well."},{"time":129000,"text":"But on a larger scale of biology, actually symmetry is very important,"},{"time":132000,"text":"because it actually communicates genetic information."}]},{"cues":[{"time":134000,"text":"I've taken two pictures here and I've made them artificially symmetrical."},{"time":138000,"text":"And if I ask you which of these you find more beautiful,"},{"time":141000,"text":"you're probably drawn to the lower two."},{"time":143000,"text":"Because it is hard to make symmetry."},{"time":146000,"text":"And if you can make yourself symmetrical, you're sending out a sign"},{"time":148000,"text":"that you've got good genes, you've got a good upbringing"},{"time":151000,"text":"and therefore you'll make a good mate."},{"time":153000,"text":"So symmetry is a language which can help to communicate"},{"time":156000,"text":"genetic information."}]},{"cues":[{"time":158000,"text":"Symmetry can also help us to explain"},{"time":160000,"text":"what's happening in the Large Hadron Collider in CERN."},{"time":163000,"text":"Or what's not happening in the Large Hadron Collider in CERN."},{"time":166000,"text":"To be able to make predictions about the fundamental particles"},{"time":168000,"text":"we might see there,"},{"time":170000,"text":"it seems that they are all facets of some strange symmetrical shape"},{"time":174000,"text":"in a higher dimensional space."}]},{"cues":[{"time":176000,"text":"And I think Galileo summed up, very nicely,"},{"time":178000,"text":"the power of mathematics"},{"time":180000,"text":"to understand the scientific world around us."},{"time":182000,"text":"He wrote, \"The universe cannot be read"},{"time":184000,"text":"until we have learnt the language"},{"time":186000,"text":"and become familiar with the characters in which it is written."},{"time":189000,"text":"It is written in mathematical language,"},{"time":191000,"text":"and the letters are triangles, circles and other geometric figures,"},{"time":195000,"text":"without which means it is humanly impossible"},{"time":197000,"text":"to comprehend a single word.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":200000,"text":"But it's not just scientists who are interested in symmetry."},{"time":203000,"text":"Artists too love to play around with symmetry."},{"time":206000,"text":"They also have a slightly more ambiguous relationship with it."},{"time":209000,"text":"Here is Thomas Mann talking about symmetry in \"The Magic Mountain.\""},{"time":212000,"text":"He has a character describing the snowflake,"},{"time":215000,"text":"and he says he \"shuddered at its perfect precision,"},{"time":218000,"text":"found it deathly, the very marrow of death.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":221000,"text":"But what artists like to do is to set up expectations"},{"time":223000,"text":"of symmetry and then break them."},{"time":225000,"text":"And a beautiful example of this"},{"time":227000,"text":"I found, actually, when I visited a colleague of mine"},{"time":229000,"text":"in Japan, Professor Kurokawa."},{"time":231000,"text":"And he took me up to the temples in Nikko."},{"time":234000,"text":"And just after this photo was taken we walked up the stairs."},{"time":237000,"text":"And the gateway you see behind"},{"time":239000,"text":"has eight columns, with beautiful symmetrical designs on them."},{"time":242000,"text":"Seven of them are exactly the same,"},{"time":244000,"text":"and the eighth one is turned upside down."}]},{"cues":[{"time":247000,"text":"And I said to Professor Kurokawa,"},{"time":249000,"text":"\"Wow, the architects must have really been kicking themselves"},{"time":251000,"text":"when they realized that they'd made a mistake and put this one upside down.\""},{"time":254000,"text":"And he said, \"No, no, no. It was a very deliberate act.\""},{"time":257000,"text":"And he referred me to this lovely quote from the Japanese"},{"time":259000,"text":"\"Essays in Idleness\" from the 14th century,"},{"time":262000,"text":"in which the essayist wrote, \"In everything,"},{"time":264000,"text":"uniformity is undesirable."},{"time":267000,"text":"Leaving something incomplete makes it interesting,"},{"time":269000,"text":"and gives one the feeling that there is room for growth.\""},{"time":272000,"text":"Even when building the Imperial Palace,"},{"time":274000,"text":"they always leave one place unfinished."}]},{"cues":[{"time":278000,"text":"But if I had to choose one building in the world"},{"time":281000,"text":"to be cast out on a desert island, to live the rest of my life,"},{"time":284000,"text":"being an addict of symmetry, I would probably choose the Alhambra in Granada."},{"time":288000,"text":"This is a palace celebrating symmetry."},{"time":290000,"text":"Recently I took my family --"},{"time":292000,"text":"we do these rather kind of nerdy mathematical trips, which my family love."},{"time":295000,"text":"This is my son Tamer. You can see"},{"time":297000,"text":"he's really enjoying our mathematical trip to the Alhambra."},{"time":300000,"text":"But I wanted to try and enrich him."},{"time":303000,"text":"I think one of the problems about school mathematics"},{"time":305000,"text":"is it doesn't look at how mathematics is embedded"},{"time":307000,"text":"in the world we live in."},{"time":309000,"text":"So, I wanted to open his eyes up to"},{"time":311000,"text":"how much symmetry is running through the Alhambra."}]},{"cues":[{"time":314000,"text":"You see it already. Immediately you go in,"},{"time":316000,"text":"the reflective symmetry in the water."},{"time":318000,"text":"But it's on the walls where all the exciting things are happening."},{"time":321000,"text":"The Moorish artists were denied the possibility"},{"time":323000,"text":"to draw things with souls."},{"time":325000,"text":"So they explored a more geometric art."},{"time":327000,"text":"And so what is symmetry?"},{"time":329000,"text":"The Alhambra somehow asks all of these questions."},{"time":332000,"text":"What is symmetry? When [there] are two of these walls,"},{"time":334000,"text":"do they have the same symmetries?"},{"time":336000,"text":"Can we say whether they discovered"},{"time":338000,"text":"all of the symmetries in the Alhambra?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":341000,"text":"And it was Galois who produced a language"},{"time":343000,"text":"to be able to answer some of these questions."},{"time":346000,"text":"For Galois, symmetry -- unlike for Thomas Mann,"},{"time":349000,"text":"which was something still and deathly --"},{"time":351000,"text":"for Galois, symmetry was all about motion."},{"time":354000,"text":"What can you do to a symmetrical object,"},{"time":356000,"text":"move it in some way, so it looks the same"},{"time":358000,"text":"as before you moved it?"},{"time":360000,"text":"I like to describe it as the magic trick moves."},{"time":362000,"text":"What can you do to something? You close your eyes."},{"time":364000,"text":"I do something, put it back down again."},{"time":366000,"text":"It looks like it did before it started."}]},{"cues":[{"time":368000,"text":"So, for example, the walls in the Alhambra --"},{"time":370000,"text":"I can take all of these tiles, and fix them at the yellow place,"},{"time":374000,"text":"rotate them by 90 degrees,"},{"time":376000,"text":"put them all back down again and they fit perfectly down there."},{"time":379000,"text":"And if you open your eyes again, you wouldn't know that they'd moved."},{"time":382000,"text":"But it's the motion that really characterizes the symmetry"},{"time":385000,"text":"inside the Alhambra."},{"time":387000,"text":"But it's also about producing a language to describe this."},{"time":389000,"text":"And the power of mathematics is often"},{"time":392000,"text":"to change one thing into another, to change geometry into language."}]},{"cues":[{"time":396000,"text":"So I'm going to take you through, perhaps push you a little bit mathematically --"},{"time":399000,"text":"so brace yourselves --"},{"time":401000,"text":"push you a little bit to understand how this language works,"},{"time":404000,"text":"which enables us to capture what is symmetry."},{"time":406000,"text":"So, let's take these two symmetrical objects here."},{"time":409000,"text":"Let's take the twisted six-pointed starfish."},{"time":411000,"text":"What can I do to the starfish which makes it look the same?"},{"time":414000,"text":"Well, there I rotated it by a sixth of a turn,"},{"time":417000,"text":"and still it looks like it did before I started."},{"time":419000,"text":"I could rotate it by a third of a turn,"},{"time":422000,"text":"or a half a turn,"},{"time":424000,"text":"or put it back down on its image, or two thirds of a turn."},{"time":427000,"text":"And a fifth symmetry, I can rotate it by five sixths of a turn."},{"time":431000,"text":"And those are things that I can do to the symmetrical object"},{"time":434000,"text":"that make it look like it did before I started."}]},{"cues":[{"time":437000,"text":"Now, for Galois, there was actually a sixth symmetry."},{"time":440000,"text":"Can anybody think what else I could do to this"},{"time":442000,"text":"which would leave it like I did before I started?"},{"time":445000,"text":"I can't flip it because I've put a little twist on it, haven't I?"},{"time":448000,"text":"It's got no reflective symmetry."},{"time":450000,"text":"But what I could do is just leave it where it is,"},{"time":453000,"text":"pick it up, and put it down again."},{"time":455000,"text":"And for Galois this was like the zeroth symmetry."},{"time":458000,"text":"Actually, the invention of the number zero"},{"time":461000,"text":"was a very modern concept, seventh century A.D., by the Indians."},{"time":464000,"text":"It seems mad to talk about nothing."},{"time":467000,"text":"And this is the same idea. This is a symmetrical --"},{"time":469000,"text":"so everything has symmetry, where you just leave it where it is."}]},{"cues":[{"time":471000,"text":"So, this object has six symmetries."},{"time":474000,"text":"And what about the triangle?"},{"time":476000,"text":"Well, I can rotate by a third of a turn clockwise"},{"time":480000,"text":"or a third of a turn anticlockwise."},{"time":482000,"text":"But now this has some reflectional symmetry."},{"time":484000,"text":"I can reflect it in the line through X,"},{"time":486000,"text":"or the line through Y,"},{"time":488000,"text":"or the line through Z."},{"time":490000,"text":"Five symmetries and then of course the zeroth symmetry"},{"time":493000,"text":"where I just pick it up and leave it where it is."},{"time":496000,"text":"So both of these objects have six symmetries."},{"time":499000,"text":"Now, I'm a great believer that mathematics is not a spectator sport,"},{"time":502000,"text":"and you have to do some mathematics"},{"time":504000,"text":"in order to really understand it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":506000,"text":"So here is a little question for you."},{"time":508000,"text":"And I'm going to give a prize at the end of my talk"},{"time":510000,"text":"for the person who gets closest to the answer."},{"time":512000,"text":"The Rubik's Cube."},{"time":514000,"text":"How many symmetries does a Rubik's Cube have?"},{"time":517000,"text":"How many things can I do to this object"},{"time":519000,"text":"and put it down so it still looks like a cube?"},{"time":521000,"text":"Okay? So I want you to think about that problem as we go on,"},{"time":524000,"text":"and count how many symmetries there are."},{"time":526000,"text":"And there will be a prize for the person who gets closest at the end."}]},{"cues":[{"time":530000,"text":"But let's go back down to symmetries that I got for these two objects."},{"time":534000,"text":"What Galois realized: it isn't just the individual symmetries,"},{"time":537000,"text":"but how they interact with each other"},{"time":539000,"text":"which really characterizes the symmetry of an object."},{"time":543000,"text":"If I do one magic trick move followed by another,"},{"time":546000,"text":"the combination is a third magic trick move."},{"time":548000,"text":"And here we see Galois starting to develop"},{"time":550000,"text":"a language to see the substance"},{"time":553000,"text":"of the things unseen, the sort of abstract idea"},{"time":555000,"text":"of the symmetry underlying this physical object."},{"time":558000,"text":"For example, what if I turn the starfish"},{"time":561000,"text":"by a sixth of a turn,"},{"time":563000,"text":"and then a third of a turn?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":565000,"text":"So I've given names. The capital letters, A, B, C, D, E, F,"},{"time":568000,"text":"are the names for the rotations."},{"time":570000,"text":"B, for example, rotates the little yellow dot"},{"time":573000,"text":"to the B on the starfish. And so on."},{"time":576000,"text":"So what if I do B, which is a sixth of a turn,"},{"time":578000,"text":"followed by C, which is a third of a turn?"},{"time":581000,"text":"Well let's do that. A sixth of a turn,"},{"time":583000,"text":"followed by a third of a turn,"},{"time":585000,"text":"the combined effect is as if I had just rotated it by half a turn in one go."},{"time":590000,"text":"So the little table here records"},{"time":592000,"text":"how the algebra of these symmetries work."},{"time":595000,"text":"I do one followed by another, the answer is"},{"time":597000,"text":"it's rotation D, half a turn."},{"time":599000,"text":"What I if I did it in the other order? Would it make any difference?"},{"time":602000,"text":"Let's see. Let's do the third of the turn first, and then the sixth of a turn."},{"time":606000,"text":"Of course, it doesn't make any difference."},{"time":608000,"text":"It still ends up at half a turn."}]},{"cues":[{"time":610000,"text":"And there is some symmetry here in the way the symmetries interact with each other."},{"time":615000,"text":"But this is completely different to the symmetries of the triangle."},{"time":618000,"text":"Let's see what happens if we do two symmetries"},{"time":620000,"text":"with the triangle, one after the other."},{"time":622000,"text":"Let's do a rotation by a third of a turn anticlockwise,"},{"time":625000,"text":"and reflect in the line through X."},{"time":627000,"text":"Well, the combined effect is as if I had just done the reflection in the line through Z"},{"time":631000,"text":"to start with."},{"time":633000,"text":"Now, let's do it in a different order."},{"time":635000,"text":"Let's do the reflection in X first,"},{"time":637000,"text":"followed by the rotation by a third of a turn anticlockwise."},{"time":641000,"text":"The combined effect, the triangle ends up somewhere completely different."},{"time":644000,"text":"It's as if it was reflected in the line through Y."}]},{"cues":[{"time":647000,"text":"Now it matters what order you do the operations in."},{"time":650000,"text":"And this enables us to distinguish"},{"time":652000,"text":"why the symmetries of these objects --"},{"time":654000,"text":"they both have six symmetries. So why shouldn't we say"},{"time":656000,"text":"they have the same symmetries?"},{"time":658000,"text":"But the way the symmetries interact"},{"time":660000,"text":"enable us -- we've now got a language"},{"time":662000,"text":"to distinguish why these symmetries are fundamentally different."},{"time":665000,"text":"And you can try this when you go down to the pub, later on."},{"time":668000,"text":"Take a beer mat and rotate it by a quarter of a turn,"},{"time":671000,"text":"then flip it. And then do it in the other order,"},{"time":673000,"text":"and the picture will be facing in the opposite direction."}]},{"cues":[{"time":677000,"text":"Now, Galois produced some laws for how these tables -- how symmetries interact."},{"time":681000,"text":"It's almost like little Sudoku tables."},{"time":683000,"text":"You don't see any symmetry twice"},{"time":685000,"text":"in any row or column."},{"time":687000,"text":"And, using those rules, he was able to say"},{"time":691000,"text":"that there are in fact only two objects"},{"time":693000,"text":"with six symmetries."},{"time":695000,"text":"And they'll be the same as the symmetries of the triangle,"},{"time":698000,"text":"or the symmetries of the six-pointed starfish."},{"time":700000,"text":"I think this is an amazing development."},{"time":702000,"text":"It's almost like the concept of number being developed for symmetry."},{"time":706000,"text":"In the front here, I've got one, two, three people"},{"time":708000,"text":"sitting on one, two, three chairs."},{"time":710000,"text":"The people and the chairs are very different,"},{"time":713000,"text":"but the number, the abstract idea of the number, is the same."}]},{"cues":[{"time":716000,"text":"And we can see this now: we go back to the walls in the Alhambra."},{"time":719000,"text":"Here are two very different walls,"},{"time":721000,"text":"very different geometric pictures."},{"time":723000,"text":"But, using the language of Galois,"},{"time":725000,"text":"we can understand that the underlying abstract symmetries of these things"},{"time":728000,"text":"are actually the same."},{"time":730000,"text":"For example, let's take this beautiful wall"},{"time":732000,"text":"with the triangles with a little twist on them."},{"time":735000,"text":"You can rotate them by a sixth of a turn"},{"time":737000,"text":"if you ignore the colors. We're not matching up the colors."},{"time":739000,"text":"But the shapes match up if I rotate by a sixth of a turn"},{"time":742000,"text":"around the point where all the triangles meet."},{"time":745000,"text":"What about the center of a triangle? I can rotate"},{"time":747000,"text":"by a third of a turn around the center of the triangle,"},{"time":749000,"text":"and everything matches up."},{"time":751000,"text":"And then there is an interesting place halfway along an edge,"},{"time":753000,"text":"where I can rotate by 180 degrees."},{"time":755000,"text":"And all the tiles match up again."},{"time":758000,"text":"So rotate along halfway along the edge, and they all match up."}]},{"cues":[{"time":761000,"text":"Now, let's move to the very different-looking wall in the Alhambra."},{"time":765000,"text":"And we find the same symmetries here, and the same interaction."},{"time":768000,"text":"So, there was a sixth of a turn. A third of a turn where the Z pieces meet."},{"time":773000,"text":"And the half a turn is halfway between the six pointed stars."},{"time":777000,"text":"And although these walls look very different,"},{"time":779000,"text":"Galois has produced a language to say"},{"time":782000,"text":"that in fact the symmetries underlying these are exactly the same."},{"time":785000,"text":"And it's a symmetry we call 6-3-2."}]},{"cues":[{"time":788000,"text":"Here is another example in the Alhambra."},{"time":790000,"text":"This is a wall, a ceiling, and a floor."},{"time":793000,"text":"They all look very different. But this language allows us to say"},{"time":796000,"text":"that they are representations of the same symmetrical abstract object,"},{"time":800000,"text":"which we call 4-4-2. Nothing to do with football,"},{"time":802000,"text":"but because of the fact that there are two places where you can rotate"},{"time":805000,"text":"by a quarter of a turn, and one by half a turn."}]},{"cues":[{"time":809000,"text":"Now, this power of the language is even more,"},{"time":811000,"text":"because Galois can say,"},{"time":813000,"text":"\"Did the Moorish artists discover all of the possible symmetries"},{"time":816000,"text":"on the walls in the Alhambra?\""},{"time":818000,"text":"And it turns out they almost did."},{"time":820000,"text":"You can prove, using Galois' language,"},{"time":822000,"text":"there are actually only 17"},{"time":824000,"text":"different symmetries that you can do in the walls in the Alhambra."},{"time":828000,"text":"And they, if you try to produce a different wall with this 18th one,"},{"time":831000,"text":"it will have to have the same symmetries as one of these 17."}]},{"cues":[{"time":836000,"text":"But these are things that we can see."},{"time":838000,"text":"And the power of Galois' mathematical language"},{"time":840000,"text":"is it also allows us to create"},{"time":842000,"text":"symmetrical objects in the unseen world,"},{"time":845000,"text":"beyond the two-dimensional, three-dimensional,"},{"time":847000,"text":"all the way through to the four- or five- or infinite-dimensional space."},{"time":850000,"text":"And that's where I work. I create"},{"time":852000,"text":"mathematical objects, symmetrical objects,"},{"time":854000,"text":"using Galois' language,"},{"time":856000,"text":"in very high dimensional spaces."},{"time":858000,"text":"So I think it's a great example of things unseen,"},{"time":860000,"text":"which the power of mathematical language allows you to create."}]},{"cues":[{"time":864000,"text":"So, like Galois, I stayed up all last night"},{"time":866000,"text":"creating a new mathematical symmetrical object for you,"},{"time":870000,"text":"and I've got a picture of it here."},{"time":872000,"text":"Well, unfortunately it isn't really a picture. If I could have my board"},{"time":875000,"text":"at the side here, great, excellent."},{"time":877000,"text":"Here we are. Unfortunately, I can't show you"},{"time":879000,"text":"a picture of this symmetrical object."},{"time":881000,"text":"But here is the language which describes"},{"time":884000,"text":"how the symmetries interact."}]},{"cues":[{"time":886000,"text":"Now, this new symmetrical object"},{"time":888000,"text":"does not have a name yet."},{"time":890000,"text":"Now, people like getting their names on things,"},{"time":892000,"text":"on craters on the moon"},{"time":894000,"text":"or new species of animals."},{"time":896000,"text":"So I'm going to give you the chance to get your name on a new symmetrical object"},{"time":900000,"text":"which hasn't been named before."},{"time":902000,"text":"And this thing -- species die away,"},{"time":904000,"text":"and moons kind of get hit by meteors and explode --"},{"time":907000,"text":"but this mathematical object will live forever."},{"time":909000,"text":"It will make you immortal."},{"time":911000,"text":"In order to win this symmetrical object,"},{"time":914000,"text":"what you have to do is to answer the question I asked you at the beginning."},{"time":917000,"text":"How many symmetries does a Rubik's Cube have?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":921000,"text":"Okay, I'm going to sort you out."},{"time":923000,"text":"Rather than you all shouting out, I want you to count how many digits there are"},{"time":926000,"text":"in that number. Okay?"},{"time":928000,"text":"If you've got it as a factorial, you've got to expand the factorials."},{"time":931000,"text":"Okay, now if you want to play,"},{"time":933000,"text":"I want you to stand up, okay?"},{"time":935000,"text":"If you think you've got an estimate for how many digits,"},{"time":937000,"text":"right -- we've already got one competitor here."},{"time":940000,"text":"If you all stay down he wins it automatically."},{"time":942000,"text":"Okay. Excellent. So we've got four here, five, six."},{"time":945000,"text":"Great. Excellent. That should get us going. All right."}]},{"cues":[{"time":950000,"text":"Anybody with five or less digits, you've got to sit down,"},{"time":953000,"text":"because you've underestimated."},{"time":955000,"text":"Five or less digits. So, if you're in the tens of thousands you've got to sit down."},{"time":959000,"text":"60 digits or more, you've got to sit down."},{"time":962000,"text":"You've overestimated."},{"time":964000,"text":"20 digits or less, sit down."},{"time":968000,"text":"How many digits are there in your number?"},{"time":973000,"text":"Two? So you should have sat down earlier."},{"time":975000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":976000,"text":"Let's have the other ones, who sat down during the 20, up again. Okay?"},{"time":980000,"text":"If I told you 20 or less, stand up."},{"time":982000,"text":"Because this one. I think there were a few here."},{"time":984000,"text":"The people who just last sat down."}]},{"cues":[{"time":987000,"text":"Okay, how many digits do you have in your number?"},{"time":992000,"text":"(Laughs)"},{"time":995000,"text":"21. Okay good. How many do you have in yours?"},{"time":997000,"text":"18. So it goes to this lady here."},{"time":1000000,"text":"21 is the closest."},{"time":1002000,"text":"It actually has -- the number of symmetries in the Rubik's cube"},{"time":1004000,"text":"has 25 digits."},{"time":1006000,"text":"So now I need to name this object."},{"time":1008000,"text":"So, what is your name?"},{"time":1010000,"text":"I need your surname. Symmetrical objects generally --"},{"time":1013000,"text":"spell it for me."},{"time":1015000,"text":"G-H-E-Z"},{"time":1022000,"text":"No, SO2 has already been used, actually,"},{"time":1024000,"text":"in the mathematical language. So you can't have that one."},{"time":1026000,"text":"So Ghez, there we go. That's your new symmetrical object."},{"time":1028000,"text":"You are now immortal."},{"time":1030000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1036000,"text":"And if you'd like your own symmetrical object,"},{"time":1038000,"text":"I have a project raising money for a charity in Guatemala,"},{"time":1041000,"text":"where I will stay up all night and devise an object for you,"},{"time":1044000,"text":"for a donation to this charity to help kids get into education in Guatemala."},{"time":1048000,"text":"And I think what drives me, as a mathematician,"},{"time":1051000,"text":"are those things which are not seen, the things that we haven't discovered."},{"time":1055000,"text":"It's all the unanswered questions which make mathematics a living subject."},{"time":1059000,"text":"And I will always come back to this quote from the Japanese \"Essays in Idleness\":"},{"time":1062000,"text":"\"In everything, uniformity is undesirable."},{"time":1065000,"text":"Leaving something incomplete makes it interesting,"},{"time":1068000,"text":"and gives one the feeling that there is room for growth.\" Thank you."},{"time":1071000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}